      >
        <h4>Understanding ECN Execution</h4>
        <p>Both brokers route orders directly to liquidity providers - no dealing desk. But the infrastructure behind this matters for serious traders.</p>

        <h5>Execution Speed: Does 10ms Matter?</h5>
        <p>Pepperstone averages 30ms execution, IC Markets around 40ms. Is 10ms significant? For most traders, no. For high-frequency EAs executing hundreds of trades daily, potentially yes. For discretionary traders, you'll never notice the difference.</p>

        <h5>Liquidity Providers</h5>
        <p>IC Markets aggregates from 25+ liquidity providers, Pepperstone from 20+. More LPs generally means tighter spreads during volatile periods and better fill rates on large orders. For standard retail sizes (under 10 lots), both provide identical fills.</p>

        <h5>Server Locations</h5>
        <p>Pepperstone operates from NY4, LD5, and TY3 (New York, London, Tokyo). IC Markets from NY4 and LD5. If you're trading Asian sessions heavily and want minimal latency, Pepperstone's Tokyo server is an advantage. For most Western traders, both have optimal NY/London proximity.</p>

        <h5>Free VPS Hosting</h5>
        <p>Both offer free VPS when you meet volume requirements (typically 15+ lots/month). The VPS is co-located near their servers, giving EAs sub-5ms execution. Essential for latency-sensitive strategies.</p>

        <h5>The Scalper's Verdict</h5>
        <p>For pure scalping, Pepperstone's faster execution gives a theoretical edge. For high-volume trading during news, IC Markets' deeper liquidity helps. In practice, top scalpers succeed with both brokers. Your strategy matters more than the 10ms difference.</p>
